Question 1.

Calculate the mean, sum of squared deviations (SS), variance, and standard deviation for the following set of numbers and assume they represent an entire population:

\(x = [6,9,0,4,7,-4]\)

Click here for solution


Mean (\(\mu\)): \[ \mu = \frac{\sum(x)}{n} = \frac{6 + 9 + 0 + 4 + 7 + -4}{6} = 3.667 \]


Sum of Squared Deviations (\(SS\)):


\(\begin{aligned} (x - \mu)^2 &= \\ (6 - 3.667)^2 &= 5.443 \\ (9 - 3.667)^2 &= 28.441 \\ (0 - 3.667)^2 &= 13.447 \\ (4 - 3.667)^2 &= 0.111 \\ (7 - 3.667)^2 &= 11.109 \\ (-4 - 3.667)^2 &= 58.783 \end{aligned}\)


\(\begin{aligned} SS &= \sum(x - \mu)^2 \\ &= 5.443 + 28.441 + 13.447 + 0.111 + 11.109 + 58.783 \\ &= 117.334 \end{aligned}\)


Population Variance (\(\sigma^2\)):


\(\sigma^2 = \frac{\sum(x - \mu)^2}{N} = \frac{117.334}{6} = 19.556\)


Population Standard Deviation (\(\sigma\)):


\(\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{\sum(x - \mu)^2}{N}} = \sqrt{\frac{117.334}{6}} = 4.422\)




Question 2.

Assume the data from Question 1 is normally distributed, calculate the interval the middle 95% of the data fall within.

Click here for solution


From question 1:

\(\mu = 3.667\)

\(\sigma = 4.422\)


The middle 95% is two standard deviations from the mean. Thus . . .

\(\begin{aligned} 3.667 - 2 \times 4.422 &= -5.177\\ 3.667 + 2 \times 4.422 &= 12.511\\ \end{aligned}\)


The middle 95% of the data fall within the interval \([-5.177, 12.511]\).

The middle 68% of the data fall within the interval \([-0.755, 8.089]\).




Question 4.

Calculate the mean, sum of squared deviations (SS), variance, and standard deviation for the following set of numbers and assume they represent a sample of data:

\(x = [161,195,110,127,113,104]\)

Click here for solution


Mean (\(\bar{x}\)): \[ \bar{x} = \frac{\sum(x)}{n} = \frac{161 + 195 + 110 + 127 + 113 + 104}{6} = 135 \]


Sum of Squared Deviations (\(SS\)):


\(\begin{aligned} (x - \bar{x})^2 &= \\ (161 - 135)^2 &= 676 \\ (195 - 135)^2 &= 3600 \\ (110 - 135)^2 &= 625 \\ (127 - 135)^2 &= 64 \\ (113 - 135)^2 &= 484 \\ (104 - 135)^2 &= 961 \end{aligned}\)


\(\begin{aligned} SS &= \sum(x - \bar{x})^2 \\ &= 676 + 3600 + 625 + 64 + 484 + 961 \\ &= 6410 \end{aligned}\)


Sample Variance (\(s^2\)):


\(s^2 = \frac{\sum(x - \bar{x})^2}{N-1} = \frac{6410}{5} = 1282\)


Sample Standard Deviation (\(s\)):


\(s = \sqrt{\frac{\sum(x - \bar{x})^2}{N-1}} = \sqrt{\frac{6410}{5}} = 35.805\)

The middle 95% of the data fall within the interval \([63.39, 206.61]\).

Question 9.

Bobby’s brother constantly tells him he’s abnormal. To prove this, his brother obtained the test scores of Bobby and his classmates.

His classmates scored \(70, 68, 75, 72, 76, 74, 69, 82, 73\).

Bobby scored a \(56\).

If “abnormal” is operationally defined as being at least \(2\) standard deviations away from the mean, is Bobby abnormal? (Use population level statistics).

Click here for solution


Calculating \(z\) (i.e., a “z-score”) will tell you how far (in standard deviations) a specific value is from the mean.

Make sure to include Bobby in your calculation of the mean and standard deviation because he is a member of the class too!

The mean and standard deviation of this data set are:

\(\mu = 71.5\)

\(\sigma = 6.423\)


Therefore:

\(z = \frac{x_i - \mu}{\sigma} = \frac{56 - 71.5}{6.423} = -2.413\)

Bobby’s score is 2.413 standard deviations below the mean (because \(z\) is negative). Since \(2.413\) is greater than \(2\), Bobby’s brother is (technically) correct. Bobby is abnormal.

Another approach to solving this would be to calculate the middle 95% interval and see if Bobby’s score falls outside of it.




Question 10.

Given question 9, what range of scores would Bobby need to fall within to be considered “normal”?

Click here for solution


“Abnormal” here is being defined as greater than \(2\) standard deviations away from the mean. Thus the interval to be considered normal is . . .

\(\begin{aligned} 71.5 - 2 \times 6.423 = 58.654\\ 71.5 + 2 \times 6.423 = 84.346 \end{aligned}\)

\([58.654, 84.346]\)




Question 11.

What is the population mean, sum of squared deviations (SS), variance, and standard deviation for the following distribution of numbers: 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, and 4? Why do you think the answer turned out the way it did?

Click here for solution


\(\begin{aligned} &\mu = 4.0 \\ &SS = 0.0 \\ &\sigma^2 = 0.0 \\ &\sigma = 0.0 &\end{aligned}\)


The data has no spread (i.e. does not vary/deviate); hence our statistical measures of spread (the sum of squared deviations, variance, and standard deviation) are just 0.

Each bar shows the number of times a certain value was rolled. Therefore . . .


Population and Sample Means (\(\mu\), \(\bar{x}\)):

Note that there is no difference between how you calculate a population vs. sample mean.

Question 18.

Kristi scored \(62.5\). Her other classmates obtained the following scores:

\(60.5, 80.1, 70.5, 62.5, 56.5\)

How many standard deviations above or below the mean was Kristi in her class? Use population level statistics for this question and make sure to specify the sign (+ or -) of the value you obtain.

Click here for solution


To solve this you need to first calculate the mean and population standard deviation. And when you calculate these numbers, make sure Kristi is included.


\(\mu = 65.433\)

\(\sigma = 7.769\)

\(z = \frac{x_i - \mu}{\sigma} = \frac{62.5 - 65.433}{7.769} = -0.378\)


Kristi is \(0.378\) standard deviations below the mean.




Question 19.

People with IQ scores \(2\) standard deviations above the mean or higher are often classified as “genius”. If IQ scores have a mean of \(100\) and a standard deviation of \(15\), what is the minimum IQ score you would need to qualify as a genius?

Click here for solution


Input the values you know into the z-score formula and then solve for \(x\):


\(\begin{aligned} \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma} &= z \\ \\ \frac{x - 100}{15} &= 2 \\ \\ x - 100 &= 2 \times 15 \\ \\ x &= 2 \times 15 + 100 \\ \\ x &= 130 \end{aligned}\)




Question 20.

Brittany records the speeds of vehicles moving past their house. The speed limit is \(40\text{ km/h}\). The mean and standard deviation of \(132\) readings was \(\bar{x} = 43 \text{ km/h}\) and \(s = 5.2 \text{ km/h}\).

Assuming the data is normally distributed, what is the percent chance (approximately) that a person is travelling faster than \(45.6 \text{ km/h}\)?

Use this Standard Normal Distribution curve to help answer the question:

Click here for solution


The first step is to figure out how many standard deviations above or below the mean \(45.6 \text{ km/h}\) is.


\(z = \frac{45.6 - 43}{5.2} = 0.5\)


Then, find that point (\(0.5\)) on the curve’s x-axis and add up all the percentages to the right of that point since those would encompass values faster than 45.6 km/h.


\(15+9.2+4.4+1.7+0.5+0.1 = 30.9 \%\)

\(0.1+0.5+1.7+4.4+9.2+15+19.1+19.1 = 69.1 \%\)




Question 22.

In 1914 the famed Albertan sasquatch hunter, Balthazar Mulder Catchkins, compared the cranial capacity of \(72\) sasquatch he had tracked during his illustrious carreer of squatching.

The estimated capacity of the \(72\) different sasquatch skulls he measured was normally distributed with a mean of \(2167\) cubic centimeters and sample standard deviation of \(86.63\).

Approximately how many sasquatch in Catchkins’s sample would you expect to have cranial capcity between \(2253.63\) \(\text{cm}^3\) and \(2340.26\) \(\text{cm}^3\)?

Use this Standard Normal Distribution curve to help answer the question:

Click here for solution


The first step is to determine how many standard deviations from the mean the two values are:

\(z_{low} = \frac{2253.63 - 2167}{86.63} = 1\)


\(z_{high} = \frac{2340.26 - 2167}{86.63} = 2\)


Using the graph, establish the percentage both values encompass:


Between \(1\) and \(2\) standard deviations, we would add up the following percentages:

\(9.2+4.4 = 13.6 \%\)


Finally, calculate how much of the sample size this value represents:

\(\left ( \frac{13.6}{100} \right ) \times 72 = 9.792\)




Question 23.

Consider a normal probability distribution like the ones graphed above in questions 20 and 22. If you randomly select a value from a normal distribution, what do you think the probability of selecting a value exactly equal to the mean (\(\mu\)) is? (no calculations are needed to answer this)

Click here for solution


The probability is \(0\).

This is because the normal distribution represents continuous data. Consequently, the mean, as a single point on that distribution, is infinitesimally small with an infinite amount of values on either side of it. And it is so small that the probability of getting a value exactly equal to it is just zero.

This holds true for any single point on a continuous distribution, like the normal distribution. This is why we talk about the probability of a range of values when using the normal distribution.




Question 24.

What numbers must be included with the following set of numbers to change their current median by \(78.5\) in any direction?

\(618, 691, 99\)

Choose the correct answer from one of these four options:

  1. \(300, 809, 986\)

  2. \(439, 31, 888\)

  3. \(364, 243, 730\)

  4. \(702, 866, 802\)


Click here for solution


Answering this question will require a bit of trial and error.

First, the median of the given three numbers is: \(618\)

  • i.e., “\(618, 691, 99\)” has a median of \(618\).

Second, the median of the given three numbers combined with the numbers from option d is equal to \(696.5\).

  • i.e., \(618, 691, 99, 702, 866, 802\) has a median of \(696.5\).

Note that the change (i.e., absolute difference) in median values is \(|618 - 696.5| = 78.5\), therefore answer d is correct. If you try this with the other options you will find that the change (i.e., difference) in median values is not 78.5.

If you are wondering what the vertical line (|) brackets are, they indicate “absolute value.” I used this because we don’t care about the direction (positive or negative) of the change is. In simple terms, absolute values make everything positive.




Question 25.

Suppose the mean score on an exam is \(59.1\) with a standard deviation of \(5.1\) and that you score \(0.3\) standard deviations below the mean, what was your raw score?

Click here for solution


Put the values in the z-score formula and solve for \(x\).

\(\begin{aligned} \frac{x - \bar{x}}{s} &= z \\ \\ \frac{x - 59.1}{5.1} &= -0.3 \\ \\ x - 59.1 &= -0.3 \times 5.1 \\ \\ x &= -0.3 \times 5.1 + 59.1 \\ \\ x &= 57.57 \end{aligned}\)
